messages.content:
Creating an interactive text-based adventure game using HTML will be limited as HTML is not a programming language; it's a markup language used to structure content on the web. However, we can use JavaScript along with HTML to add the interactivity needed for a text-based game.

Below, I'll provide a simplistic version of "The Reflection Pool" puzzle from "The Mysteries of Echo Cave" to give you an idea of how you can use HTML and JavaScript to create a text-based game:

First, let's create the HTML structure:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Text Adventure Game: Echo Cave</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>The Mysteries of Echo Cave</h1>
<div id="game-container">
  <p id="description"></p>
  <input type="text" id="input" placeholder="Type here...">
  <button onclick="processInput()">Submit</button>
  <p id="message"></p>
</div>

<script src="game.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

Now the JavaScript (`game.js`) which will handle the game logic:

```javascript
let currentRoom = "awakeningChamber";
const gameData = {
  "awakeningChamber": {
    "description": "You're in a small cavern with a flickering torch on the wall. Exits lead North and South.",
  },
  "reflectionPool": {
    "description": "You see a crystal-clear pool and a locked door with a keypad. Words on the wall read: 'Gaze into the pool's mirror, where your countenance lies still. The age of your reflection, when reversed, will break the seal.'",
    "ageReversed": "21"
  }
};

// Initialize the game with the first room description.
window.onload = () => {
  document.getElementById('description').innerHTML = gameData[currentRoom].description;
};

function processInput() {
  const input = document.getElementById('input').value.toLowerCase().trim();
  document.getElementById('input').value = ""; // Clear the input.
  const messageElement = document.getElementById('message');

  if (currentRoom === "awakeningChamber") {
    if (input === "go north") {
      currentRoom = "reflectionPool";
      document.getElementById('description').innerHTML = gameData[currentRoom].description;
    } else {
      messageElement.innerText = "There's nothing that way...";
    }
  } else if (currentRoom === "reflectionPool") {
    if (input === gameData[currentRoom].ageReversed) {
      messageElement.innerText = "You hear a click! The door is now unlocked.";
      // More code to transition to the next room...
    } else {
      messageElement.innerText = "Nothing happens...";
    }
  }
}
```

This example is very basic and is meant to be expanded upon. Here's what is happening:

- When the page loads, it initializes with the description of the starting room.
- There's an input field where the player can type commands and a submit button to process those commands.
- The `processInput` function checks the player's input against expected answers and updates the game state accordingly.

Building a robust and complex text-based game often requires a more sophisticated approach to managing game states and player input. You would likely also want to use a more organized system of handling rooms, items, and puzzles, potentially storing more complex game data in JSON format or using a game development framework.
